snippet.textDisplay:
Thanks so much! This is very helpful. 

Question- when you removed the bag from the inside of the Cheerios box, you had touched the box, and then you touched the bag inside with your hands. Is that potentially transferring bad things to the bag? 

I had no idea about the virus surviving for up to two years in the freezer! :( I've been sort of relying on my freezer to kill it, although I have wiped down everything with a disinfectant prior to putting it in there.

By the way, I would love to share a version of this in which there are only plant-based foods if that's something you might do (although I'm pretty sure you don't want to redo it unless you have some new info) I think it's super important information, but that fast food is responsible for probably way more deaths than Covid ever will be.

That said, thank you so much for taking the time to do this video, and I hope you don't feel this is that last bit is too critical.

Not bad for u.s. based ideas I guess, considering your country was asleep at the switch laughing off this global pandemic since December 2019.
FYI... hand sanitizer is unavailable in 99.9% of the world and has been for about a month or more.
No mention of your vehicle steering wheel or handles, radio knobs, household door handles or even shoes, clothing, jackets once you arrive back home after being exposed to the virus while shopping.

snippet.textDisplay:
I unpacked my groceries in my garage.
I made a disinfectant solution of ⅓ cup of bleach to 1 gal water.
I wore gloves and unpacked each item, disinfected with bleach water/rag, and moved the clean items to a clean bag. Disposed of gloves, Went into the house, washed my hands, and THEN went back out to get the clean groceries. I left the original bags in the garage for 3 days.

snippet.textDisplay:
""We don't really have any evidence that food or food packaging is a source for getting sick" from COVID-19, said Benjamin Chapman, a professor and food safety specialist at North Carolina State University." "Chapman stressed that there's a lot we don't know about COVID-19 and the virus that causes it, SARS-CoV-2. Our understanding about the spread of the disease, and the risk food poses, could change as more information becomes available.

But as far as we know, the disease appears to be spread mainly from person-to-person through virus particles that are spread when someone coughs or sneezes, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). While COVID-19 can theoretically be transmitted by touching a contaminated surface and then touching your nose, mouth or eyes, that's not thought to be its primary mode of transmission, according to the CDC. "

snippet.textDisplay: That you for this.  An observation - It seems to me there was cross-contamination when you handled the contaminated cereal box and then with the same hands reached in to pull out the plastic inside.  The plastic would then be viewed as contaminated but it was placed on the clean side of the counter thereby rendering the clean side contaminated.  Seems a better approach would be to open the box and either have someone else pull out the bag or use tongs to pull it out.

snippet.textDisplay: At 5:05, you say the CDC says we can use "any standard disinfectant". This furthers my distrust of the CDC, especially having observed them closely since January. All disinfectants are not created equal in regard to coronaviruses! This analysis of 22 studies on persistence of coronaviruses on surfaces and effectiveness of biocidal agents shows the different efficacies: https://www.journalofhospitalinfection.com/article/S0195-6701(20)30046-3/fulltext Benzalkonium chloride, which is common in Lysol, does not do as well as ethanol (isopropyl alcohol) or Sodium hypochlorite (bleach).
